BTRSys2.1

Target IP: 192.168.186.50

Scanning


There are three TCP ports open on the target machine: SSH, FTP, and HTTP.

Enumeration

Port 21: FTP

This FTP application allows anonymous login. However, there are no files I can download. And I do not have write privileges. Maybe it will come in handy later?

Port 80: HTTP

Browsing to this port on a browser displays the webpage above. Clicking the GIF image opens another file called 2.gif. From the nmap scan above, it states there is a robots.txt file.


Browsing to the robots.txt page displays the message above. So we now know there is a WordPress directory.


This is the WordPress application. The source-code of this page mentions it is running the version 3.9 .14. Doing a directory search does not result in very helpful information.


Doing a wpscan with the command wpscan --url http://192.168.186.50/wordpress shows mail-masta 1.0 plugin is used.


And this plugin is vulnerable to LFI attacks!

Exploitation


According to the exploit's PoC above, it is possible to perform LFI attacks using the count_of_send.php file followed by the pl parameter and the payload.


And this worked. I used the payload http://192.168.186.50/wordpress/wp-content/plugins/mail-masta/inc/campaign/count_of_send.php?pl=/etc/passwd to obtain the /etc/passwd file. Trying to obtain the SSH key of btrisk user did not work, so it is time for fuzzing! Fuzzing did not provide me anything useful. RFI is not working, it seems like there is a firewall in place. Maybe it is time to attack the users of the website. The target machine crashed and got a new IP of 192.168.229.50.


Using the command wpscan --url http://192.168.229.50/wordpress --enumerate u -P /usr/share/wordlists/rockyou.txt, I obtained the password of the user admin.


After logging in with the credentials admin:admin, I notice the twentyfourteen theme can be changed. I will replace the 404.php file with PHP Pentest Monkey reverse shell script. After starting a listener on port 8443, I browsed to http://192.168.229.50/wp-content/themes/twentyfourteen/404.php to start the reverse shell.


And now I have my reverse shell connection and foothold on the machine.

Privilege Escalation


The config.php contains the username and password root:rootpassword!.


Using the credentials from above, I managed to gain access to the MySQL database. There is an interesting table called wp_users which contains two entries. Cracking the hash of user root a318e4507e5a74604aafb45e4741edd3 results in roottoor.


And spraying the credential root:roottoor worked as I have root privileges now.
